<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
     MODULE 2 — THE WORKFLOW JSON
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="module" id="module-2" style="background:var(--bg-warm)">
<div class="module-content">

  <header class="module-header animate-in">
    <span class="module-number">02</span>
    <h1 class="module-title">The Workflow JSON</h1>
    <p class="module-subtitle">Every workflow starts as a single text file. Here's exactly what goes in it.</p>
  </header>

  <!-- Screen 1: JSON metaphor + file location -->
  <section class="screen animate-in">
    <h2 class="screen-heading">JSON is just a labelled form in text format</h2>
    <p>Think of a JSON file like a government form — fields with labels, filled in with values. The difference is that a computer can read it. You open the file in any text editor, fill in the right fields, save it, and the site knows what to display.</p>

    <div class="file-tree animate-in">
<span class="ft-dir">📁 data/</span>
<span class="ft-dir">  📁 workflows/</span>
<span class="ft-file ft-json ft-highlight">    📄 wf-pol-001-briefing-note.json</span><span class="ft-comment">  ← your workflow file goes here</span>
<span class="ft-file ft-json">    📄 wf-pol-002-question-time-brief.json</span>
<span class="ft-file ft-json">    📄 wf-eng-001-stakeholder-analysis.json</span>
<span class="ft-file ft-json">    📄 wf-career-001-monthly-performance-check-in.json</span>
<span class="ft-dir">  📁 building-blocks/</span>
<span class="ft-file ft-json">    📄 bb-gen-001.json</span>
<span class="ft-file ft-json">    📄 bb-pol-001.json</span><span class="ft-comment">  ← one file per building block</span>
<span class="ft-dir">  📁 quality-gates/</span>
<span class="ft-file ft-json">    📄 qg-trust-001.json</span>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <p><strong>Naming convention:</strong> <code style="font-size:.82rem">wf-{"{"}domain abbreviation{"}"}-{"{"}number{"}"}-{"{"}slug{"}"}.json</code><br>
      e.g. <code style="font-size:.82rem">wf-pol-001-briefing-note.json</code> — Policy, number 001, slug "briefing-note"</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Screen 2: Code ↔ English — workflow metadata fields -->
  <section class="screen animate-in">
    <h2 class="screen-heading">The header fields — who this workflow is and what it does</h2>
    <p>The first section of a workflow JSON describes the workflow itself. Here's the real code from <code style="font-size:.82rem">wf-pol-001-briefing-note.json</code>:</p>

    <div class="translation-block">
      <div class="translation-code">
        <span class="tl-label">CODE</span>
        <pre><code><span class="cp">"id"</span><span class="co">:</span> <span class="cs">"WF-POL-001"</span>,
<span class="cp">"slug"</span><span class="co">:</span> <span class="cs">"briefing-note"</span>,
<span class="cp">"name"</span><span class="co">:</span> <span class="cs">"Briefing Note"</span>,
<span class="cp">"maturity"</span><span class="co">:</span> <span class="cs">"draft"</span>,
<span class="cp">"maturity_note"</span><span class="co">:</span> <span class="cs">"Initial implementation..."</span>,
<span class="cp">"maturity_updated"</span><span class="co">:</span> <span class="cs">"2026-03-25"</span>,
<span class="cp">"domain"</span><span class="co">:</span> <span class="cs">"policy_development"</span>,
<span class="cp">"complexity"</span><span class="co">:</span> <span class="cs">"intermediate"</span>,
<span class="cp">"estimated_time"</span><span class="co">:</span> <span class="cs">"30–45 minutes"</span></code></pre>
      </div>
      <div class="translation-english">
        <span class="tl-label">PLAIN ENGLISH</span>
        <p class="tl"><strong>id</strong> — a unique identifier. Starts with <code style="font-size:.78rem">WF-</code>, then domain code, then number. Must be unique across all workflows.</p>
        <p class="tl"><strong>slug</strong> — becomes the URL path: <code style="font-size:.78rem">/workflows/briefing-note</code>. Use lowercase with hyphens, no spaces.</p>
        <p class="tl"><strong>name</strong> — the human-readable title shown on cards and page headings.</p>
        <p class="tl tl-edit"><strong>maturity</strong> — how thoroughly it's been tested. One of: <code style="font-size:.78rem">draft</code>, <code style="font-size:.78rem">tested</code>, <code style="font-size:.78rem">reviewed</code>, <code style="font-size:.78rem">validated</code>. Safe to edit anytime.</p>
        <p class="tl tl-edit"><strong>maturity_note / maturity_updated</strong> — free text context and date. Update these whenever you change maturity.</p>
        <p class="tl"><strong>domain</strong> — which category it appears under in the browse page. Must match a known value.</p>
        <p class="tl"><strong>complexity</strong> — shown as a badge: <code style="font-size:.78rem">beginner</code>, <code style="font-size:.78rem">intermediate</code>, or <code style="font-size:.78rem">advanced</code>.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Screen 3: Steps overview -->
  <section class="screen animate-in">
    <h2 class="screen-heading">The <code style="font-size:.95rem">steps</code> array — the heart of a workflow</h2>
    <p>After the header, a workflow JSON has a <code style="font-size:.82rem">steps</code> array — a list of steps in order. Here's one step (Step 1 of the Briefing Note workflow) with each field explained:</p>

    <div class="translation-block">
      <div class="translation-code">
        <span class="tl-label">CODE</span>
        <pre><code>{"{"}<span class="cp">"order"</span><span class="co">:</span> <span class="cn">1</span>,
  <span class="cp">"id"</span><span class="co">:</span> <span class="cs">"step-1"</span>,
  <span class="cp">"name"</span><span class="co">:</span> <span class="cs">"Scope &amp; Research"</span>,
  <span class="cp">"step_type"</span><span class="co">:</span> <span class="cs">"generation"</span>,
  <span class="cp">"building_block_id"</span><span class="co">:</span> <span class="cs">"BB-GEN-001"</span>,
  <span class="cp">"trust_level"</span><span class="co">:</span> <span class="cs">"medium"</span>,
  <span class="cp">"is_optional"</span><span class="co">:</span> <span class="ck">false</span>,
  <span class="cp">"user_action_after"</span><span class="co">:</span> <span class="cs">"Review..."</span>,
  <span class="cp">"output_feeds_to"</span><span class="co">:</span> [<span class="cn">2</span>]
{"}"}</code></pre>
      </div>
      <div class="translation-english">
        <span class="tl-label">PLAIN ENGLISH</span>
        <p class="tl"><strong>order</strong> — what number this step is. Determines display sequence.</p>
        <p class="tl"><strong>id</strong> — a string identifier for the step, used internally.</p>
        <p class="tl"><strong>name</strong> — the step title shown in the workflow header.</p>
        <p class="tl"><strong>step_type</strong> — either <code style="font-size:.78rem">generation</code> (AI writes something) or <code style="font-size:.78rem">quality_gate</code> (AI reviews something).</p>
        <p class="tl tl-key"><strong>building_block_id</strong> — 🔑 this is the link to the actual prompt. Must exactly match the <code style="font-size:.78rem">id</code> in a building block JSON file.</p>
        <p class="tl tl-edit"><strong>trust_level</strong> — the badge colour: <code style="font-size:.78rem">high</code> (green), <code style="font-size:.78rem">medium</code> (amber), <code style="font-size:.78rem">low</code> (red). Safe to edit.</p>
        <p class="tl tl-edit"><strong>user_action_after</strong> — the "what to do next" callout box. Safe to edit — just plain text.</p>
        <p class="tl"><strong>output_feeds_to</strong> — which step numbers this output connects to. Used for the progress indicator.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Screen 4: Quiz 2 -->
  <section class="screen animate-in">
    <div class="quiz">
      <span class="quiz-label">🧠 Check your understanding</span>
      <p class="quiz-q">A colleague says the "what to do next" instruction box in Step 3 of a workflow is wrong — it tells users to do something that no longer applies. Which field in which file do you edit?</p>
      <div class="quiz-opts" id="q2-opts">
        <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false" onclick="handleQ('q2-opts','q2-fb',this)">Edit WorkflowLayout.astro — that's where the instruction boxes are rendered.</button>
        <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="true" onclick="handleQ('q2-opts','q2-fb',this)">Edit the <code>user_action_after</code> field in Step 3 of the workflow JSON file.</button>
        <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false" onclick="handleQ('q2-opts','q2-fb',this)">Edit the building block JSON for that step — that's where user instructions live.</button>
        <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false" onclick="handleQ('q2-opts','q2-fb',this)">Edit the Astro page file for that workflow.</button>
      </div>
      <div class="quiz-fb" id="q2-fb"></div>
    </div>
  </section>

</div>
</section>

<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
     MODULE 3 — BUILDING BLOCKS
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="module" id="module-3" style="background:var(--bg)">
<div class="module-content">

  <header class="module-header animate-in">
    <span class="module-number">03</span>
    <h1 class="module-title">Building Blocks</h1>
    <p class="module-subtitle">Where the actual AI prompts live — and how the blanks get filled in.</p>
  </header>

  <!-- Screen 1: What is a building block -->
  <section class="screen animate-in">
    <h2 class="screen-heading">A building block is a prompt with blanks</h2>
    <p>Think of a building block like a <strong>Mad Libs template</strong> — a pre-written text with specific blanks waiting to be filled in. The blanks are called <span class="tt" data-tip="Placeholders in a prompt template written as {{variable_name}}. When the workflow runs, these get replaced with the user's actual input — their topic, their agency, their audience, etc.">variables</span>, and they're written like <code style="font-size:.82rem">{"{{topic}}"}</code>.</p>

    <p>When a user fills in the input form on a workflow page and clicks "Copy", the app swaps those placeholders for the real values — producing a ready-to-paste prompt.</p>

    <div class="two-col">
      <div class="callout">
        <p><strong>Generation block</strong><br>Prompts the AI to create something — a draft, a structure, a list.</p>
        <p style="margin-top:6px;font-family:var(--font-m);font-size:.72rem;color:var(--text-m)">block_type: "generation"</p>
      </div>
      <div class="callout callout-warn">
        <p><strong>Quality gate block</strong><br>Prompts the AI to review or critique something already written. Lives in <code style="font-size:.78rem">data/quality-gates/</code>.</p>
        <p style="margin-top:6px;font-family:var(--font-m);font-size:.72rem;color:var(--text-m)">block_type: "quality_gate"</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Screen 2: Code ↔ English of a building block prompt_template -->
  <section class="screen animate-in">
    <h2 class="screen-heading">Inside a building block — the prompt template</h2>
    <p>Here's the <code style="font-size:.82rem">prompt_template</code> field from <code style="font-size:.82rem">bb-gen-001.json</code> (the Scope &amp; Research step):</p>

    <div class="translation-block">
      <div class="translation-code">
        <span class="tl-label">CODE</span>
        <pre><code><span class="ct">&lt;role&gt;</span>
You are a senior <span class="cn">{"{{policy_area}}"}</span> analyst
working in <span class="cn">{"{{agency}}"}</span>.
<span class="ct">&lt;/role&gt;</span>

<span class="ct">&lt;task&gt;</span>
Identify the key issues relevant
to a briefing note on this topic.

Topic: <span class="cn">{"{{topic}}"}</span>
Audience: <span class="cn">{"{{audience}}"}</span>
Purpose: <span class="cn">{"{{purpose}}"}</span>
<span class="ct">&lt;/task&gt;</span></code></pre>
      </div>
      <div class="translation-english">
        <span class="tl-label">PLAIN ENGLISH</span>
        <p class="tl"><strong>&lt;role&gt;</strong> — XML tags tell the AI what persona to take on. Claude especially responds well to these structured role definitions.</p>
        <p class="tl tl-key"><strong>{"{{policy_area}}"}</strong> — a variable. At runtime this becomes whatever the user typed in the "Policy area" input field. Variables must match the <code style="font-size:.78rem">name</code> in the workflow's <code style="font-size:.78rem">inputs_required</code> array.</p>
        <p class="tl tl-key"><strong>{"{{agency}}"}</strong> — same — becomes "Department of Social Services" or whatever the user entered.</p>
        <p class="tl"><strong>&lt;task&gt;</strong> — separates the role setup from the actual instruction. Good prompt engineering practice.</p>
        <p class="tl tl-key"><strong>{"{{topic}}"}</strong>, <strong>{"{{audience}}"}</strong>, <strong>{"{{purpose}}"}</strong> — all filled in from the workflow's input form.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Screen 3: Data flow animation — variables flowing in -->
  <section class="screen animate-in">
    <h2 class="screen-heading">How variables flow from the form to the prompt</h2>
    <p>When a user fills in the input form and clicks "Copy Prompt" on Step 1, here's what happens:</p>

    <div class="dflow" id="dflow-1">
      <div class="dflow-step" id="df-s1">
        <div>
          <div class="dflow-dot"></div>
          <div class="dflow-line"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="dflow-text">
          <strong>User fills the form</strong>
          <small>Topic: "NDIS participant satisfaction", Agency: "DSS", etc.</small>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="dflow-step" id="df-s2">
        <div>
          <div class="dflow-dot"></div>
          <div class="dflow-line"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="dflow-text">
          <strong>JavaScript reads <code style="font-size:.75rem">inputs_required</code> from the workflow JSON</strong>
          <small>Collects: topic, agency, audience, purpose, policy_area, length</small>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="dflow-step" id="df-s3">
        <div>
          <div class="dflow-dot"></div>
          <div class="dflow-line"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="dflow-text">
          <strong>Looks up the building block for that step</strong>
          <small>Step 1 → BB-GEN-001 → fetches its <code style="font-size:.75rem">prompt_template</code></small>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="dflow-step" id="df-s4">
        <div>
          <div class="dflow-dot"></div>
          <div class="dflow-line"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="dflow-text">
          <strong>Replaces every <code style="font-size:.75rem">{"{{variable}}"}</code> with the user's value</strong>
          <small><code style="font-size:.75rem">{"{{agency}}"}</code> → "Department of Social Services"</small>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="dflow-step" id="df-s5">
        <div>
          <div class="dflow-dot"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="dflow-text">
          <strong>Copies the finished prompt to clipboard</strong>
          <small>Ready to paste into Claude, Copilot, or ChatGPT</small>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <button class="dflow-play" id="dflow-1-btn">▶ Animate</button>

    <div class="callout callout-warn" style="margin-top:16px">
      <p>⚠️ <strong>Critical rule:</strong> every <code style="font-size:.82rem">{"{{variable_name}}"}</code> in a building block's prompt template must exactly match the <code style="font-size:.82rem">name</code> of a field in the workflow's <code style="font-size:.82rem">inputs_required</code> array. A mismatch means the variable won't be filled in — the user sees the placeholder text instead.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Screen 4: Quiz 3 -->
  <section class="screen animate-in">
    <div class="quiz">
      <span class="quiz-label">🧠 Check your understanding</span>
      <p class="quiz-q">You're adding a new building block for a workflow about Cabinet Submissions. The prompt needs the minister's name. You write <code style="font-size:.85rem">{"{{minister_name}}"}</code> in the template. What else needs to match?</p>
      <div class="quiz-opts" id="q3-opts">
        <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false" onclick="handleQ('q3-opts','q3-fb',this)">Nothing — WorkflowLayout will automatically detect the new variable and add an input field.</button>
        <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="true" onclick="handleQ('q3-opts','q3-fb',this)">The workflow JSON needs an entry in <code>inputs_required</code> with <code>name: "minister_name"</code> — that's what creates the form field.</button>
        <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false" onclick="handleQ('q3-opts','q3-fb',this)">You add <code>minister_name</code> to the Astro page file's <code>blocks</code> object.</button>
        <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false" onclick="handleQ('q3-opts','q3-fb',this)">The variable name doesn't need to match anything — it's just display text in the prompt.</button>
      </div>
      <div class="quiz-fb" id="q3-fb"></div>
    </div>
  </section>

</div>
</section>

<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
     MODULE 4 — ADDING A NEW WORKFLOW
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="module" id="module-4" style="background:var(--bg-warm)">
<div class="module-content">

  <header class="module-header animate-in">
    <span class="module-number">04</span>
    <h1 class="module-title">Adding a New Workflow</h1>
    <p class="module-subtitle">The exact recipe — three files, in the right places, wired together correctly.</p>
  </header>

  <!-- Screen 1: The three files -->
  <section class="screen animate-in">
    <h2 class="screen-heading">Three files. That's all.</h2>
    <p>To add a new workflow (say, "Cabinet Submission"), you create exactly three things:</p>

    <div class="step-cards stagger-children">
      <div class="step-card animate-in">
        <div class="step-num">1</div>
        <div class="step-body">
          <div class="step-title">One workflow JSON file</div>
          <div class="step-text">Defines the workflow: title, domain, steps, required inputs, skill guidance. This is the main content file.</div>
          <span class="step-file">data/workflows/wf-pol-003-cabinet-submission.json</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-card animate-in">
        <div class="step-num">2</div>
        <div class="step-body">
          <div class="step-title">One building block JSON per step</div>
          <div class="step-text">Each step that uses AI needs its own building block file containing the prompt template. A 5-step workflow needs up to 5 building blocks (reusable blocks from other workflows can be shared).</div>
          <span class="step-file">data/building-blocks/bb-cab-001.json</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-card animate-in">
        <div class="step-num">3</div>
        <div class="step-body">
          <div class="step-title">One Astro page file</div>
          <div class="step-text">A tiny file — usually just 20-odd lines — that imports the JSON files and passes them to WorkflowLayout. That's literally all it does.</div>
          <span class="step-file">src/pages/workflows/cabinet-submission.astro</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout callout-ok">
      <p>✅ <strong>You never touch WorkflowLayout.astro</strong> when adding a new workflow. The layout handles all the rendering — trust levels, copy buttons, platform tips, progress bars. It just needs to receive the data.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Screen 2: Code ↔ English — the Astro page file -->
  <section class="screen animate-in">
    <h2 class="screen-heading">The Astro page file is surprisingly small</h2>
    <p>Here's the <em>entire</em> <code style="font-size:.82rem">briefing-note.astro</code> file — exactly as it appears in the codebase. A new workflow page looks identical to this, just with different filenames:</p>

    <div class="translation-block">
      <div class="translation-code">
        <span class="tl-label">CODE (briefing-note.astro — complete file)</span>
        <pre><code><span class="cc">---</span>
<span class="ck">import</span> WorkflowLayout <span class="ck">from</span>
  <span class="cs">'../../layouts/WorkflowLayout.astro'</span>;
<span class="ck">import</span> workflow <span class="ck">from</span>
  <span class="cs">'../../../data/workflows/wf-pol-001-briefing-note.json'</span>;
<span class="ck">import</span> bb001 <span class="ck">from</span>
  <span class="cs">'../../../data/building-blocks/bb-gen-001.json'</span>;
<span class="ck">import</span> bb002 <span class="ck">from</span>
  <span class="cs">'../../../data/building-blocks/bb-gen-002.json'</span>;
<span class="ck">import</span> qgTrust <span class="ck">from</span>
  <span class="cs">'../../../data/quality-gates/qg-trust-001.json'</span>;

<span class="ck">const</span> blocks = {"{"}
  <span class="cp">'BB-GEN-001'</span>: bb001,
  <span class="cp">'BB-GEN-002'</span>: bb002,
  <span class="cp">'QG-TRUST-001'</span>: qgTrust,
{"}"};
<span class="cc">---</span>

<span class="ct">&lt;WorkflowLayout</span> <span class="ca">workflow</span>=<span class="cs">{"{"}</span>workflow<span class="cs">{"}"}</span> <span class="ca">blocks</span>=<span class="cs">{"{"}</span>blocks<span class="cs">{"}"}</span> <span class="ct">/&gt;</span></code></pre>
      </div>
      <div class="translation-english">
        <span class="tl-label">PLAIN ENGLISH</span>
        <p class="tl"><strong>The <code style="font-size:.78rem">---</code> fences</strong> mark the <span class="tt" data-tip="The code section at the top of an Astro file, between --- markers. It runs on the server at build time and can import files, fetch data, and run JavaScript logic.">frontmatter</span> — code that runs at build time before the page HTML is output.</p>
        <p class="tl"><strong>import WorkflowLayout</strong> — load the shared layout template. Path goes up two levels (<code style="font-size:.78rem">../../</code>) from the page file to reach <code style="font-size:.78rem">src/layouts/</code>.</p>
